Recall that a morphism σ: A^* → A^* is said to be everywhere growing if it does not admit bounded letter , i.e., letter b such that lim_n → +∞|σ^n(b)|<+∞. We let A_𝔅,σ (or A_𝔅 when no confusion is possible) denote the set of bounded letters of σ. By opposition, a non-bounded letter is called a growing letter. Since for all letters a, we have |σ^n(a)| ∈Θ(n^α_aβ_a^n) for some α_a in ℕ and β_a ≥ 1 (see <cit.>), any everywhere growing morphism satisfies exactly one of the following three definitions:


  * a morphism σ: A^* → A^* is quasi-uniform if there exists β≥ 1 such that for all letters a ∈ A, |σ^n(a)| ∈Θ(β^n);


  * a morphism σ: A^* → A^* is polynomially diverging if there exists β >1 and a function α: A →ℕ, α≠ 0, such that for all letters a ∈ A, |σ^n(a)| ∈Θ(n^α(a)β^n);


  * a morphism σ: A^* → A^* is exponentially diverging if there exist a_1,a_2 ∈ A, α_1,α_2 ∈ℕ and β_1,β_2 >1 with β_1 ≠β_2 such that for each i ∈{1,2}, |σ^n(a_i)| ∈Θ(n^α_iβ_i^n).

